<concept
	id="oql_compared_to_sql">
	<title>Advantages of OQL</title>
	<prolog>
		<metadata>
			<keywords>
				<keyword>gemfire OQL</keyword>
			</keywords>
		</metadata>
	</prolog>
	<conbody>
		<p>The following list describes some of the advantages of using an OQL-based querying
			language: </p>
			<ul
				id="ul_D0CE1C54DEB14221A8CA18FD21A9B12A">
				<li
					id="li_0CC6C825E3754DB386FB0FE8D0D0A6D6">You can query on any arbitrary object </li>
				<li
					id="li_F1ACDC9252D2412C9EB749C0A867A500">You can navigate object collections </li>
				<li
					id="li_8E4CD513A01040E19A1BFECFD47E03E8">You can invoke methods and access the
					behavior of objects </li>
				<li
					id="li_156EFB6E7A7A49A6A70FA6BED759EC84">Data mapping is supported </li>
				<li
					id="li_18F6F4994B3743D8B3018A304D0C52DC">You are not required to declare types.
					Since you do not need type definitions, you can work across multiple languages </li>
				<li
					id="li_99C7FBBCA877481386BEAE9138EF4AF6">You are not constrained by a schema
				</li>
			</ul>
	</conbody>
</concept>
